      <h1>Information for GPs</h1>

<p>Dear General Practitioner,</p>

<p>You have been directed to this page as your patient has shown interest in participating in our online exercise study, called Train for the Brain. We would like to thank you in advance for any assistance or support which you may provide for our project. Exercise is a great way of staying healthy but it can sometimes increase the risk of an adverse reaction, especially in those who have a pre-existing condition or an ongoing health problem.</p>
<p>With this in mind, we have advised your patient to seek your consult and discuss any health concerns they have around their fitness to participate. To assist you in this, we would like to offer you some information on the study and the exercise programmes your patient may be getting involved in.</p>

<h2>What is Train for the Brain?</h2>
<p>Train for the Brain is a double blind, randomized controlled trial looking to examine the feasibility of an online self-directed exercise intervention in older adults. The study is open to all UK based volunteers over the age of 50 who have access to a computer and who do not have a medical diagnosis of dementia.</p>
<p>The study will be delivered online for a period of six months, during which time participants will be encouraged to complete a six-week physical exercise regime – treatment or control.</p>
<p>As part of the study, participants will also complete a number of assessments on cognition, mood, goal attainment and physical health. The study has received ethical approval by the .... (ref no..) and is being conducted by King’s College London and the University of Exeter.</p>

<h2>Why has my patient been invited?</h2>
<p>Your patient has been invited to take part in this study as he/she is part of the Platform for Research Online to investigate Cognition and Genetics in Ageing (PROTECT). PROTECT is a 10- year study looking to determine the role of genetics, lifestyle and medical factors on cognition. It also has the added function of providing a unique platform for online clinical trial delivery, and will be supporting the delivery of the Train for the Brain study.</p>
<p>PROTECT is ‘home’ for a cohort of over 20,000 adults over the age of 50 and has already hosted two large clinical trials with success. PROTECT has ethical approval from the NHS Research Ethics Service Committee for London Bridge (Ref: 13/ LO/1578).</p>
