<h2>What do the exercise programmes involve?</h2>
<p>Should your patient decide to take part in the study, they will be randomly allocated to a treatment or control group.</p>

<h2>Treatment group (‘Train for the Brain’)</h2>
<p>As part of the study’s safety measures, participants will automatically be placed into one of three ability-dependent exercise groups before commencing on the Train for the Brain exercise programme. Stratification will be based on information reported by the participant regarding their medical history and current level of physical fitness.</p>
<p>Participants who require the assistance of a walking aid or who report a recent cardiovascular condition and/ or frequent falls, will automatically be placed in our low-intensity activity group. Once stratified, your patient will be encouraged to complete 150 minutes of physical activity a week in bouts of 30 minute exercise sessions.</p>
<p>The Train for the Brain intervention comprises a variety of video workouts and a complementary walking programme, and has been designed with the focus on meeting the physical activity needs of older adults.</p>
<p>Each workout is pre-recorded and led by a physiotherapist or dance therapist who provides step-by-step, verbal and visual instructions to ensure correct workout execution and help avoid participant injury.</p>
<p>The sessions comprise a 5 minute mandatory warm up, 20 minutes of self-elected exercise chosen from a variety of aerobics, dance, Pilates and cardiovascular work, and a 5 minute cool down.</p>
<p>The intervention will last for a duration of six weeks; each week commencing with a short, educational welcome video containing interviews of experts in the field and written information on the benefits of physical activity. The intervention is delivered purely online and participants will be able to access their sessions from the comfort of their own home.</p>

<h2>Control group</h2>
<p>If your patient is allocated to the control group we will provide them with written information on government recommended physical activity guidelines for older adults. This will consist of brief information on the benefits and the optimal duration and length of physical activity, as well as some ideas and examples of physical activities that can be taken. This information will be available to participants for a duration of six weeks.</p>

<h3>Adverse events</h3>
<p>Your patient will be monitored throughout the course of the study for the presence of adverse events. This information will be collected on a weekly basis through a self-reported electronic case report form (eCRF) and direct notification from the participant, their family or yourself. The information will be reviewed and recorded by a qualified clinician within our team.</p>
<p>All serious adverse events that are unexpected and deemed to be related to the trial will be reported to the Research Ethics Committee by the study Principal Investigator, Dr Anne Corbett. In the unlikely event of an adverse reaction, we may contact your patient and/or your practice to collect further information.</p>

<h2>Further information</h2>
<p>As this is a double-blind, placebo controlled study our participants will not be informed of the specific content of the exercise programmes (treatment or control). With this in mind, we would appreciate your cooperation and help in ensuring that our participants remain blinded to their treatment.</p>
